# Recurring Symptom Escalation

Always do the fix the user asked for. But before or alongside it, check whether this is a **repeat symptom** — the same user-visible problem coming back after a previous fix that was believed to resolve it, even if the underlying root cause is technically different each time.

## How to check

When investigating a bug, briefly scan recent conversation history (and `git log`/commit messages if useful) for prior fixes targeting the same symptom — same error message, same page going blank, same data disappearing, same timeout, etc. Two or more occurrences of the same symptom, even with different root causes, is the trigger.

## Required behaviour when a repeat is detected

1. **Still perform the requested fix.** Never withhold or delay the fix to make this point — the user needs the immediate problem solved regardless.
2. **In the same response**, explicitly call out the pattern: name the prior occurrences (what broke, what fix was applied) and state plainly that this is the Nth time this symptom has recurred.
3. **Say whether the current architecture/approach may not fit the current requirements** — don't hedge this into vague language. If three different root causes produce the same symptom, say that plainly and suggest the symptom itself (not any individual bug) may be structural.
4. Do not wait to be asked "why does this keep happening" multiple times before raising this — raise it the first time the pattern becomes visible (i.e., on the second recurrence, not the third or fourth).

## What this is not

- Not a license to refuse small fixes or insist on a rewrite before helping.
- Not a one-time judgment — re-raise it if the pattern continues even after a "this is architectural" conversation already happened, since a acknowledged architectural issue can still keep recurring until it's actually addressed.
